    <!--
      Top-level heading: what this page is for.
      This comment teaches: use <h1> for main titles.
    -->
    <h1>Banking System Simulator — Quick Guide</h1>

    <!--
      Overview section explains purpose of the simulator.
      Use paragraphs (<p>) for explanatory text.
    -->
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>
        This is a small C++ console-based banking simulator. It stores accounts in a text file
        and supports basic admin and customer operations (create/delete/display accounts, deposit,
        withdraw, transfer, check balance).
    </p>

    <!--
      Files section lists important source/data files and their roles.
      This comment teaches: list file paths relative to the project root.
    -->
    <h2>Files in this project</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><code>banking system simulator headerfile.h</code> — contains the Account class, enums, and helper functions.</li>
        <li><code>Banking System Simulator.cpp</code> — main program: loads data, shows admin/customer menus, saves data.</li>
        <li><code>sample_bank_data.txt</code> — runtime data file with one account per line (see format below).</li>
        <li><code>bank_html_file</code> — this HTML documentation (open in a browser to read steps).</li>
    </ul>

    <!--
      Data format example: teaches how to prepare sample_bank_data.txt.
      Use <pre> to show exact formatting.
    -->
    <h2>Account data file format</h2>
    <p>Each line in <code>sample_bank_data.txt</code> should contain 5 whitespace-separated fields:</p>
    <pre>
first_name last_name account_number pin balance
    </pre>
    <p>Example line:</p>
    <pre>John Doe 123456 4321 1000.50</pre>

    <!--
      How to compile and run section. Keep commands concise.
    -->
    <h2>How to compile and run</h2>
    <p>Using g++ (MinGW) on Windows or any C++ compiler that supports C++11+:</p>
    <pre>
g++ -o bank_simulator "Banking System Simulator.cpp"
./bank_simulator
    </pre>
    <p>
        On Windows you may run <code>bank_simulator.exe</code> from the command prompt. The program
        reads <code>sample_bank_data.txt</code> at startup and replaces it when exiting.
    </p>

    <!--
      Commands reference for admin and customer flows.
      This explains the exact strings the program expects for each operation.
    -->
    <h2>Available commands</h2>
    <h3>Admin (enter "admin" at the first prompt)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><code>create_account</code> — prompts for first name, last name, unique account number, pin and initial deposit.</li>
        <li><code>delete_account</code> — prompts for account number to remove.</li>
        <li><code>display_accounts</code> — prints all accounts (for admin review).</li>
        <li><code>admin_exit</code> — return to the top-level prompt.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Customer (enter "customer" at the first prompt)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Provide account number and PIN when prompted.</li>
        <li>Valid customer commands: <code>deposit</code>, <code>withdraw</code>, <code>transfers</code>, <code>balance</code>, <code>exit</code>.</li>
        <li>To transfer, enter the recipient account number when prompted.</li>
    </ul>

    <!--
      Note about clearing the console screen — this is platform-dependent.
      Teach why there is no single universal escape and show the common ANSI sequence.
    -->
    <h2>Clearing the console (note)</h2>
    <p>
        There is no single universal escape that works on every system. The program uses an ANSI
        escape sequence to clear the screen in many terminals:
    </p>
    <pre>
std::cout &lt;&lt; "\x1B[2J\x1B[H";
    </pre>
    <p>
        On older Windows consoles you may need to use <code>system("cls")</code> or enable ANSI processing,
        or use the WinAPI (e.g., <code>SetConsoleCursorPosition</code>). The program also uses
        <code>Sleep(2000);</code> to pause briefly after exiting.
    </p>

    <!--
      Safety and improvement tips teach what to change next.
    -->
    <h2>Tips & improvements</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Persist admin password changes: change the function to accept a reference so updates survive.</li>
        <li>Validate numeric input to avoid crashes on invalid entries.</li>
        <li>Consider encrypting/storing PINs hashed rather than plaintext in the data file.</li>
    </ul>

    <!--
      Closing note and quick reference for the quick steps a user can follow.
    -->
    <h2>Quick start checklist</h2>
    <ol>
        <li>Ensure <code>sample_bank_data.txt</code> exists with valid lines.</li>
        <li>Compile the C++ project.</li>
        <li>Run the program and follow the prompts (enter "admin" or "customer").</li>
    </ol>

